    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="1374"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1374">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 412.11/71.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1327.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 23, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: As a result of the continued disturbed state of
                    this country the Embassy is in almost daily receipt of enquiries from citizens
                    of the United States, who have suffered loss and damage to their properties,
                    concerning what action they shall take in the matter of their claims against the
                    Government of Mexico.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to request that the Department of State instruct the Embassy in
                    the premises. At the present time I am treating these cases precisely as they
                    were treated in the last revolution.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
